{"parentUuid":"b0f4d8bc-af29-46fc-93d5-9f09d0ee4723","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aef50341d109baea0","attachment":{"type":"skill_listing","content":"- build-run: Build, and optionally run, the MWA local development environment (CoreFlow core + client repos). TRIGGER when the user says \"/build-run\", \"build and run\", \"start the app/server\", \"nuke the db\", or wants to spin up the MWA local dev stack. Handles separate core/client git repos, Maven builds, app startup on :8080, health poll, and auth-token retrieval.\n- explain: Generate textbook-quality technical documentation and explanations — for any codebase or topic, not just one project. TRIGGER when the user asks to \"explain\", \"document\", \"teach me\", \"write up\", or \"understand in depth\" a system, algorithm, or concept, or wants a deep-dive / reference doc authored. Produces rigorous-but-accessible material with formulas, legends, plain-English readings, motivating stories, real data, and in-chapter exercises. (This is the generalized form of the style the IUL textbook was written in.)\n- jetbrains-debugger: Guide for using JetBrains IDE Debugger MCP tools to programmatically debug applications. TRIGGER when ANY of these MCP tools are available: list_run_configurations, execute_run_configuration, start_debug_session, stop_debug_session, get_debug_session_status, list_debug_sessions, set_breakpoint, remove_breakpoint, list_breakpoints, resume_execution, pause_execution, step_over, step_into, step_out, run_to_line, wait_for_pause, get_stack_trace, select_stack_frame, list_threads, get_variables, set_variable, get_source_context, evaluate_expression. Use when debugging any application, investigating bugs, tracing execution flow, inspecting runtime state, or when the user says \"debug\", \"breakpoint\", \"step through\", \"inspect variable\", \"why is this returning X\", \"trace execution\", or similar debugging-related requests. PREFER the debugger over reading code and guessing when runtime behavior is unclear.\n- jira-worklog: Log, correct, backfill, or comment Jira time entries (worklogs) for PennRiver/MWA — reconstructed from REAL git/PR evidence, never fabricated. TRIGGER when the user wants to log/fix/backfill their timesheet or hours, add comments to time entries, reconcile a month of worklogs, or when their scrum master (e.g. Tom) asks to \"fix your time entries\" or \"add comments\". ALSO covers the recurring MONTHLY ROUTINE: build a forward day-by-day sprint/month schedule (board-reconciled, business-days-minus-market-holidays, story-point-paced, plain-sentence daily targets) that the worklog is later reconstructed against. Handles the Jira worklog REST API safely (read-before-write, paginate, verify-after-write).\n- pennriver: Entry point and knowledge index for the Penn River / CoreFlow (YAAS) platform and the Modern Woodmen of America (MWA) IUL project (plan 893). TRIGGER when working in the core or modern-woodmen repos, or when the user mentions PennRiver, CoreFlow, YAAS, MWA, IUL, Solvrays, the quote engine, or asks \"where is X documented\", \"what's the status of MWA-###\", or to pull a Confluence/Jira page. Points to the companion skills and gives on-demand access to all Confluence pages + Jira issues. Holds the engineering design-decision log.\n- pennriver-board: Pull the MWA sprint board (your assigned tickets, or the whole sprint) and reconcile each ticket's Jira status against where its code ACTUALLY is in git — feature branch → sprint → edge → released. TRIGGER when the user asks \"what should I work on\", \"show my board / my tickets\", \"sprint status\", \"standup prep\", \"what's actually done vs what Jira says\", wants to reconcile Jira against git/PR reality, or pastes a Jira board/JQL link. Part of the pennriver family.\n- pennriver-codebase: The Penn River / CoreFlow (YAAS) platform internals and the codebase/engineering workflow. TRIGGER when reading or changing code in the core or modern-woodmen repos; when the user mentions OSGi, Apache Karaf, the Calculator framework, callWithInput, DtoClassDescriptor/DtoGassGenerator, Plan XML, policy structure, coverage layers, transactions, the JAX-RS API framework, @Filterable; when adding a policy field/API; or when asking about repo layout, branching, or the pull-request / code-review workflow. Part of the pennriver skill family.\n- pennriver-deploy: Building, CI/CD, and deploying the Penn River / CoreFlow + Modern Woodmen system — including the monthly sprint-release runbook and the edge hotfix path. TRIGGER when the user wants to deploy, cut a sprint release, promote a build (edge → dev → UAT → staging → prod), build images, update an ECS/EKS deployment, generate a deploy changelog, rotate DB credentials, or asks about environments and the approval gate. Part of the pennriver skill family.\n- pennriver-iul: Indexed Universal Life (IUL) business logic, math, and the quote engine for the Modern Woodmen plan 893 product on CoreFlow. TRIGGER when working on premiums, cost of insurance (COI), net amount at risk (NAR), cash value, indexed/fixed strategies, the no-lapse guarantee, Section 7702/7702A / MEC / 7-pay, surrender charges, riders, monthiversary/sweepiversary/anniversary processing, lapse, or the policy quote endpoint and its calculator pipeline. Part of the pennriver skill family.\n- pennriver-mwa-api: The Modern Woodmen of America (MWA) client integration surface on CoreFlow — REST API endpoints, third-party integrations, file extracts, and test data. TRIGGER when working with MWA REST endpoints (policy/quote/premium/death/address/correspondence/rate/flags), Solvrays correspondence letters, Benekiva claims, SSO/SAML, file extracts (NACHA, Sovos/1099-R, Accounting, Billing, General Ledger, ODS full file), ODS Party/Policy/Transaction fields, or labtrial gold-copy test data. Part of the pennriver skill family.\n- update-postman: Sync the CoreFlow Postman collection (docs/api/CoreFlow.postman_collection.json) with the JAX-RS endpoints defined in the core (yaas-ws) and modern-woodmen (MwaWs) repos. Code is the source of truth — add missing endpoints, remove stale ones, update changed method/path. Preserves Auth folder, pre-request scripts, and collection variables.\n- build-run: Build, and optionally run, the MWA local development environment.\n- deploy: Deploy to an AWS ECS environment. Handles branching, builds, and deployment.\n- explain: Explain: Generate a Comprehensive Technical Textbook\n- pennriver: Load up all PennRiver/MWA project context. Use this at the start of a session to get oriented.\n- pr: Create a pull request for the current branch following PennRiver's PR standards.\n- test-certs: Run premium payment events on all certs and verify policy state.\n- deep-research: Deep research harness — fan-out web searches, fetch sources, adversarially verify claims, synthesize a cited report. - When the user wants a deep, multi-source, fact-checked research report on any topic. BEFORE invoking, check if the question is specific enough to research directly — if underspecified (e.g., \"what car to buy\" without budget/use-case/region), ask 2-3 clarifying questions to narrow scope. Then pass the refined question as args, weaving the answers in.\n- update-config: Use this skill to configure the Claude Code harness via settings.json. Automated behaviors (\"from now on when X\", \"each time X\", \"whenever X\", \"before/after X\") require hooks configured in settings.json - the harness executes these, not Claude, so memory/preferences cannot fulfill them. Also use for: permissions (\"allow X\", \"add permission\", \"move permission to\"), env vars (\"set X=Y\"), hook troubleshooting, or any changes to settings.json/settings.local.json files. Examples: \"allow npm commands\", \"add bq permission to global settings\", \"move permission to user settings\", \"set DEBUG=true\", \"when claude stops show X\". For simple settings like theme/model, suggest the /config command.\n- keybindings-help: Use when the user wants to customize keyboard shortcuts, rebind keys, add chord bindings, or modify ~/.claude/keybindings.json. Examples: \"rebind ctrl+s\", \"add a chord shortcut\", \"change the submit key\", \"customize keybindings\".\n- verify: Verify that a code change actually does what it's supposed to by running the app and observing behavior. Use when asked to verify a PR, confirm a fix works, test a change manually, check that a feature works, or validate local changes before pushing.\n- code-review: Review the current diff for correctness bugs and reuse/simplification/efficiency cleanups at the given effort level (low/medium: fewer, high-confidence findings; high→max: broader coverage, may include uncertain findings; ultra: deep multi-agent review in the cloud). Pass --comment to post findings as inline PR comments, or --fix to apply the findings to the working tree after the review.\n- simplify: Review the changed code for reuse, simplification, efficiency, and altitude cleanups, then apply the fixes. Quality only — it does not hunt for bugs; use /code-review for that.\n- fewer-permission-prompts: Scan your transcripts for common read-only Bash and MCP tool calls, then add a prioritized allowlist to project .claude/settings.json to reduce permission prompts.\n- loop: Run a prompt or slash command on a recurring interval (e.g. /loop 5m /foo). Omit the interval to let the model self-pace. - When the user wants to set up a recurring task, poll for status, or run something repeatedly on an interval (e.g. \"check the deploy every 5 minutes\", \"keep running /babysit-prs\"). Do NOT invoke for one-off tasks.\n- schedule: Create, update, list, or run scheduled cloud agents (routines) that execute on a cron schedule. - When the user wants to schedule a recurring cloud agent, set up automated tasks, create a cron job for Claude Code, or manage their scheduled agents/routines. Also use when the user wants a one-time scheduled run (\"run this once at 3pm\", \"remind me to check X tomorrow\").\n- claude-api: Reference for the Claude API / Anthropic SDK — model ids, pricing, params, streaming, tool use, MCP, agents, caching, token counting, model migration.\nTRIGGER — read BEFORE opening the target file; don't skip because it \"looks like a one-liner\" — whenever: the prompt names Claude/Anthropic in any form (Claude, Anthropic, Fable, Opus, Sonnet, Haiku, `anthropic`, `@anthropic-ai`, `claude-*`, `us.anthropic.*`, `[1m]`); the user asks about an LLM (pricing/model choice/limits/caching) — never answer from memory; OR the task is LLM-shaped with provider unstated (agent/MCP/tool-definition/multi-agent/RAG/LLM-judge/computer-use; generate/summarize/extract/classify/rewrite/converse over NL; debugging refusals/cutoffs/streaming/tool-calls/tokens).\nSKIP only when another provider is being worked on (overrides all triggers): OpenAI/GPT/Gemini/Llama/Mistral/Cohere/Ollama named in the query; OR `grep -rE 'openai|langchain_openai|google.generativeai|genai|mistralai|cohere|ollama'` over the project hits (run this grep FIRST if no provider named — don't Read the file).\n- run: Launch and drive this project's app to see a change working. Use when asked to run, start, or screenshot the app, or to confirm a change works in the real app (not just tests). First looks for a project skill that already covers launching the app; otherwise falls back to built-in patterns per project type (CLI, server, TUI, Electron, browser-driven, library).\n- init: Initialize a new CLAUDE.md file with codebase documentation\n- review: Review a pull request\n- security-review: Complete a security review of the pending changes on the current branch","skillCount":31,"isInitial":true,"names":["build-run","explain","jetbrains-debugger","jira-worklog","pennriver","pennriver-board","pennriver-codebase","pennriver-deploy","pennriver-iul","pennriver-mwa-api","update-postman","build-run","deploy","explain","pennriver","pr","test-certs","deep-research","update-config","keybindings-help","verify","code-review","simplify","fewer-permission-prompts","loop","schedule","claude-api","run","init","review","security-review"]},"type":"attachment","uuid":"023e8f79-fb8b-4d61-8e48-1be2c9036067","timestamp":"2026-06-17T18:32:05.787Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/riz/git/dotfiles","sessionId":"2cde58bf-2f4b-4d9c-ade9-87cc9f7b1872","version":"2.1.179","gitBranch":"main","slug":"snappy-stargazing-quasar"}
